(1, 'Programing', 'Coding', 'first Post', 'This website uses first-party and third-party cookies to ensure you get the best experience on our website. Learn more\r\nGot it!\r\nPaper CheckerHomeFeaturesPricingHelp / FAQsLog In\r\n\r\n \r\nAfter four years on Pennsylvania Avenue, Washington, D.C., the equivalent of Broadway, the Donald Trump Show is on the road, though it attracts younger viewers. According to a recent Gallup poll, 38% approve of his \"performance\" and 59% disapprove, a 19% gap. Even outside of Broadway, at his convention in Tulsa, Oklahoma, for example, there were empty seats, and the overflow area was closed due to limited availability. At the time, the Joe Biden Show (a type of non-show made mostly from his Delaware base) has attracted growing interest. A majority of the recent polls show Biden with an 8-12% greater lead over Trump. Biden also has attracted more investors than Trump, who has achieved excellent presidential financial performance over the past two months and in the last quarter. By those steps, Biden\'s candidate would do well by sitting on his basement. The common understanding is that people are frustrated by the lack of presidential leadership during the coronavirus and the protest issues. The president\'s campaign to take a second term is often a reference to his first four years in office, so that\'s an important point. It is also important that the strong economy that the President plans to re-work on has been removed. I would say differently, though. I would say that disrupting the president, who likes to work more than the administration, may seem tempting to the theory but it\'s very difficult to let go. If you remember the Trump fundraising campaign, it was that someone outside of Washington needed to come and \"hack the swimming pool\" - or disrupt the corrupt system. As Yuval Levin states in his latest book, A Time to Build, Trump is the first president ever to have formed and shaped American institutions such as the military, big corporations, legislature, or governor\'s office. He came into the presidency from a family and well-known businessman, which is why he can. As a celebrity president, Trump is more into tweets and speeches than official accomplishments or policy initiatives. As veteran of the campaign Karl Rove recently pointed out, he will still have to tell the American people what he will do when he is elected to the second term. His presidency is not about agendas and policies but about him - his values and his frustration, supported by his foundation. But it is difficult to treat the government that way, and in the end, that is exactly what we expected the president to do. Afterwards Biden, then, appeared to be able to form a government. His work is composed of the Senate and the president. In the face of the latest challenges, Biden has developed some tips on what to do with the coronavirus challenge, for example. Her communications are more about policies and programs than her complaints and concerns. It looks like you have a desire to govern. Frustration and disruption have their place, but it is difficult to lead an institution from that foundation. Leadership as a profession has long been part of politics, but never has a political leader ever tried to invest so much in those who have shown little interest in policy and governance. It looks like the Trump Show may not be renewed for long. Critics have never liked it, but now, without his strong base, even the audience seems tired of it. Unemployment from an informed electoral base seems appropriate to receive tributes and tweets, interruptions and Trump\'s approval petition. As British Prime Minister Harold Wilson famously said, \"The church has been a long time in politics.\" We\'ll have to keep our eye on the floor and the floor for another couple of months. David Davenport is a participant in the Washington Examiner\'s Beltway Confidential. He is a research fellow at the Hoover Institution and a visiting scholar with the Orrin G. Hatch Foundation. He is a co-author\r\n100%  original\r\nCongratulations! This paper seems to be original.\r\nNOTE: redundant sources may not be shown.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSubmit Another Document?\r\n\r\nUpload File\r\n...or paste your text here\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n I have read and agree to the terms of service below:\r\nTERMS OF USE\r\n\r\nEffective Date and Last Updated: December 17, 2019\r\n\r\n\r\nWelcome to the U.S. e-commerce shops, digital platforms, websites, applications (\"apps\"), widgets, blogs, or other online offerings owned or operated by subsidiaries of Barnes & Noble Education, Inc., including Barnes & Noble College Booksellers, LLC; MBS Textbook Exchange, LLC; Student Brands, LLC; or any of their affiliates or subsidiary companies (collectively, \"BNED\"), including but not limited to bncollege.com; bartleby.com; mbsbooks.com, studymode.com, cram.com, paperrater.com, and all other online offerings (collectively, the \"Services\") that post links to these Terms of Use. The Services include the online bookstores operated by BNED on behalf higher education and primary education institutions, as well as other online Services, resources, forums, contests or sweepstakes offered or operated by BNED.\r\n\r\nPlease review these Terms of Use carefully before using the Services. The Terms of Use govern each user’s (\"you\" or \"your\") use of and/or access to the Services.\r\n\r\nBy using or accessing the Services, you acknowledge and agree that you have read, understood and agree to be bound by these Terms of Use. You also acknowledge that you have read and understood our data practices as described in the Privacy Policy applicable to the Services and Content you use.\r\n\r\nThese Terms of Use affect your legal rights, responsibilities and obligations, govern your use of the Services, are legally binding, limit BNED’s liability to you, and require you to indemnify us and to settle certain disputes through individu